##Raw Signal ➔ Preprocessing ➔ Feature Extraction ➔ SMOTE Balancing ➔ CNN-LSTM Model ➔ Stage Prediction

Phase 1: Signal Preprocessing & IHR Extraction
The objective is to convert raw ECG voltage into a clean, uniformly sampled heart rate signal.

Data Cleaning: Normalization using patient-wise Z-score scaling and Band-pass filtering (0.5 – 40 Hz) to eliminate baseline wander.

Peak Detection: Identification of R-peaks to calculate R-R intervals.

IHR Generation: Computing the Instantaneous Heart Rate (IHR) to represent cardiac dynamics.

Interpolation: 4Hz linear interpolation to ensure all input windows have identical dimensions.

Phase 2: Feature Engineering & Dual-Domain Analysis
We merge time-domain dynamics with spectral information to provide a rich feature set.

Time-Domain: Utilizing the raw IHR signal.

Frequency-Domain: Extracting spectral features via Welch’s method, including LF, HF, lf_nu, hf_nu, and the LF/HF ratio.

Data Balancing (SMOTE): Generating synthetic samples for minority classes (N1 and N3) to ensure the model doesn't overlook light or deep sleep stages.

Augmentation: Injecting Gaussian noise and time-shifting to prevent overfitting and improve robustness.

Phase 3: Hybrid CNN-LSTM Architecture
The core of the system is designed to extract both instantaneous morphology and sequential patterns.

1D-ResNet (Spatial Extractor): Analyzes the morphology of the IHR and spectral features to identify stage-specific patterns.

Bidirectional LSTM (Temporal Modeler): Processes a sequence of 5 consecutive 30s windows. This allows the model to "remember" previous stages and "anticipate" transitions, mimicking how human experts score sleep.

Phase 4: Output & Evaluation
Classification: Softmax output layer for 5-stage classification (Wake, N1, N2, N3, REM).

Performance Metrics: Validation through Confusion Matrices and F1-scores, achieving a competitive 63% accuracy using only ECG data.
